---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const sourceUrl = "https://github.com/Zwin-ux/arbitrage";
const docsRoot = "https://github.com/Zwin-ux/arbitrage/tree/main/docs";
---

<BaseLayout title="Docs | Superior">
  <section class="page-hero compact">
    <p class="eyebrow">Docs</p>
    <h1>Read the product, inspect the code, and keep the trust story visible.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The site stays light on purpose. The source of truth is still the monorepo, the desktop app, and the trust docs that explain paper mode, local storage, and live gating in plain language.
    </p>
    <div class="hero-actions">
      <a class="button primary" href={sourceUrl} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Open GitHub</a>
      <a class="button secondary" href={`${docsRoot}/first-paper-run.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">First paper run</a>
      <a class="button secondary" href={`${docsRoot}/release-checklist.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Release checklist</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-grid">
    <article class="doc-card">
      <h2>Quick start</h2>
      <pre><code>python -m pip install -e ".[dev]"
market-data-recorder-app
market-data-recorder record</code></pre>
    </article>
    <article class="doc-card">
      <h2>Release build</h2>
      <pre><code>powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File scripts/bootstrap-iscc.ps1
powershell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File scripts/build-windows-release.ps1</code></pre>
    </article>
    <article class="doc-card">
      <h2>Quality gates</h2>
      <pre><code>pytest -q
python -m mypy src tests
market-data-recorder-qa --headless --output .tmp/qa-report.json
npm --prefix site ci
npm --prefix site run build</code></pre>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="section-grid">
    <article class="feature-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Key repo docs</p>
      <h3>Trust surface</h3>
      <p>Read the risk model, live-trading limitations, privacy and secrets notes, release checklist, first paper run guide, contributor strategy guide, release process, and third-party notices directly in the repo.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Product posture</p>
      <h3>Paper first, live gated</h3>
      <p>Superior is stable software with explicit guardrails, not a promise of profits. Users onboard, record local books, inspect explainable routes, and build paper history before any live-gate path appears.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Railway setup</p>
      <h3>Deploy only the site</h3>
      <p>Connect the GitHub repo to Railway, set the service root to <code>/site</code>, set the config path to <code>/site/railway.toml</code>, use the default Railway domain, and enable "Wait for CI". The app runtime, user data, and secrets stay off Railway.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">QA client</p>
      <h3>Review evidence directly</h3>
      <p>The public QA client runs deterministic onboarding, scanner, paper-session, benchmark, experimental-live, and live-gate scenarios and exports a JSON report with scenario artifacts. It is part of the product, not an internal-only script.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Release trust</p>
      <h3>Hashes and release manifest</h3>
      <p>Each Windows release should publish installer and portable-zip hashes. Until signing exists, the release manifest and the public repo are the trust story.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="feature-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Support</p>
      <h3>Launch issues cleanly</h3>
      <p>Use the onboarding and bug issue templates in the repo if the installer, first paper run, or connector flow breaks. Those templates are meant to shorten diagnosis, not deflect users.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
